✅ [DEBUG] MODEL-ANSWER RESPONSE (Group 19):
<span class="model_question">
The diagram shows a cone. The radius of the base of the cone is $\frac{3}{4}$ of the height of the cone. The total surface area of the cone is $54\pi~cm^{2}$. Work out the height of the cone.
</span>
<div class="model_answer">
Let the height of the cone be $h$. Then the radius of the base is $\frac{3}{4}h$. <br>
The slant height $l$ satisfies $l^2 = h^2 + (\frac{3}{4}h)^2 = h^2 + \frac{9}{16}h^2 = \frac{25}{16}h^2$, so $l = \frac{5}{4}h$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
The curved surface area is $\pi r l = \pi (\frac{3}{4}h)(\frac{5}{4}h) = \frac{15}{16}\pi h^2$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
The area of the base is $\pi r^2 = \pi (\frac{3}{4}h)^2 = \frac{9}{16}\pi h^2$. <br>
The total surface area is $\frac{15}{16}\pi h^2 + \frac{9}{16}\pi h^2 = \frac{24}{16}\pi h^2 = \frac{3}{2}\pi h^2$. <br>
So $\frac{3}{2}\pi h^2 = 54\pi$. <br>
$h^2 = \frac{2}{3} \times 54 = 2 \times 18 = 36$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
$h = \sqrt{36} = 6$. <br>
The height of the cone is $6$ cm. <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span>
</div>

